               <p>WILLIAM MASON. I am servant to Mr. Stephens, who is a <rs id="t18180909-61-viclabel338" type="occupation">linen-draper</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18180909-61-victim556 t18180909-61-viclabel338"></join>, and lives at <placeName id="t18180909-61-crimeloc339">Aldgate</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18180909-61-crimeloc339" type="placeName" value="Aldgate"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18180909-61-crimeloc339" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18180909-61-off336 t18180909-61-crimeloc339"></join>. On the 6th of August the prisoner came into the shop to match a handkerchief - I shewed her some, and saw her pull a piece towards her bundle, which laid on the counter with a basket. Soon afterwards, I saw her put her own handkerchief over the piece, and her bundle covering both. She put them under her arm, and made towards the door. I stopped her; she trembled, and begged I would forgive her. She dropped it from under her arm.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. ARABIN. I am certain I saw her drop it.</p>
               <p>JEREMIAH BEWLEY. I am servant to Mr. Stephens. I saw the prisoner in the shop.</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I have been in town but three weeks. The piece of handkerchief got entangled with my bundle.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18180909-61-verdict340" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18180909-61-verdict340" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               NOT GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>London Jury, before Mr. Common Sergeant.</p>
